etymologies: mid 19th century (earlier (mid 17th century) as supination): back-formation from supination, from Latin supinatio(n-), from supinare ‘lay backwards’, from supinus (see supine)

definitions: turn or hold (a hand, foot, or limb) so that the palm or sole is facing upward or outward

examples.text: the clinician notes the magnitude of force that is required to supinate the foot from its resting position

shortDefinitions: turn or hold hand, foot, or limb so that palm or sole is facing upwards or outwards

definitions: walk or run with most of the weight on the outside of the feet.
shortDefinitions: walk or run with most of weight on outside of feet
